Unix is an older, proprietary operating system family developed at Bell Labs, known for stability, while Linux is a free, open-source, Unix-like OS created by Linus Torvalds, inspired by Unix but with a modular kernel, widely used across PCs, servers, and mobile devices due to its flexibility and community support. Both are powerful multitasking systems, but Linux offers more customization, broad hardware support, and is free, unlike traditional Unix.
